@book{kraay2007,
  title = {Negotiating Identities in Modern {{Latin America}}},
  editor = {Kraay, Hendrik},
  year = {2007},
  series = {Turning Points: {{Occasional}} Papers in {{Latin American}} Studies},
  number = {3},
  publisher = {{Univ. of Calgary Press}},
  address = {{Calgary}},
  isbn = {978-1-55238-229-5},
  langid = {english},
  note = {Notas de Chemax
\par
El texto trata el fen\'omeno de la identificaci\'on con un lugar en la construcci\'on general de identidades individuales y grupales.
\par
{$>$}Places are usually physical or material entities, like a birthplace, and at the same time they are depositories of memory, expectation, and affection p. 216
\par
Las *dimensiones experienciales del lugar* ~son aquellas que evocan el sentido de pertenencia a un grupo social y generan un sentido de identidad grupal.
\par
{$>$}Anne Buttimer states that ``people's sense of both personal and cultural identity is intimately bound up with place identity,'' which has many dimensions including those of a ``symbolic, emotional, cultural, political and biological'' nature p. 217
\par
Un lugar provee la certeza de que uno es capaz de describirse a s\'i mismo, as\'i como de que tiene acceso a un modo de hacer las cosas que no es accesible para los extranjeros p. 217
\par
La noci\'on de lugar no es est\'atica sino construida y *manufacturada*, reflejo de relaciones sociales, por lo cual no s\'olo hay que enfocarse en la expresi\'on f\'isica del lugar, sino tambi\'en en su construcci\'on social [@kraay2007, pp. 217-218]
\par
Em Chemax la identidad del lugar, denominada *Cah* (lugar de afliaci\'on, p. 230), sobresale en la regi\'on, hay un fuerte vinculo de identidad de lugar.
\par
El lugar sirve como artefacto identitario y cultural porque permite concretar los procesos de diferenciaci\'on
\par
En Chemax, *\guillemotleft Mechanized agriculture is virtually impossible on this rocky landscape\guillemotright * [@kraay2007, p. 220]
\par
{$>$}During the twentieth century, the presence of the Mexican state increased in Chemax with highway construction, the imposition of the municipal government structures which overlaid existing political and social institutions, the introduction of the ejido system of collective land tenure through which the agriculturists of Chemax obtained formal recognition of the forest held by the cah, and the gradual incursion of state education and health institutions [@kraay2007, p. 222]}
}

